<br>
Once you have made a conscious decision to kill another human being, you're beyond consequences, and likely fully convinced you're going to get away with it. The punishment is not the deterrent, it's the possibility of not getting away with it. Honestly, is there any difference between Death and Life in Prison? Personally, I'd see a life sentence as a FAR worse punishment, but that is neither here nor there. My point here is I support the death penalty insofar as a solution to prison overcrowding, but do not agree with it as a deterrent to future crimes (unless of course, you're talking about the condemned, he certainly won't be commiting any more). <br>
<br>
But anyway, it's my opinion, not trying to make it yours  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
